{"title_page": "Kirroughtree", "text_new": "{{short description|Mountain biking routes in Galloway, Scotland}}\n{{Infobox forest|map=Scotland|map_caption=|relief=yes|county=Dumfries and Galloway|country=Scotland|coordinates={{Coord|54|57|14|N|4|25|18|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}|photo=Cycle Trail in Kirroughtree Forest - geograph.org.uk - 431790.jpg|photo_caption=Cycle Trail in Kirroughtree Forest}}{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n \n'''Kirroughtree Forest''' is located near [[Newton Stewart]] in [[Dumfries and Galloway]], southwest [[Scotland]] and overlooks the [[Irish Sea]]. It is managed by [[Forestry and Land Scotland]] and is part of the [[Galloway Forest Park]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/visit/forest-parks/galloway-forest-park|title=Galloway Forest Park|website=Forestry and Land Scotland|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> It has been developed as a centre for [[mountain biking]] trails. \n\nPalnure Burn is a small river which runs through the forest and on into the [[River Cree]]. The forest is home to red squirrels, red deer and ospreys.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/visit/forest-parks/galloway-forest-park/kirroughtree-visitor-centre|title=Kirroughtree Visitor Centre - Forestry and Land Scotland|last=|first=|date=|website=forestryandland.gov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Tourism ==\nKirroughtree atrracts about 78,000 visitors a year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/blog/investing-and-growing-the-visitor-footfall-and-the-profile-of-the-national-forest-estate|title=Investing and growing the visitor footfall and the profile of the National Forest Estate|last=|first=|date=|website=Forestry and Land Scotland|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Mountain biking ===\nKirroughtree is a [[mountain biking]] centre, which is one of 7 venues of the [[7Stanes]] project throughout the [[Scottish Borders]] and Dumfries and Galloway.<ref name=\":0\" /> 7stanes was started by the [[Forestry Commission]] in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://headwaterseconomics.org/wp-content/uploads/Trail_Study_81-7stanes-economic-impact.pdf|title=7 Stanes Phase 2 Evaluation|last=|first=|date=October 2007|website=Headwater Economics|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Chris Ross of the Forestry Commission led the design and construction of the Kirroughtree trails.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://singletrackworld.com/forum/topic/who-designed-and-constructed-the-7-stanes/|title=Who designed and constructed the 7 stanes?|last=|first=|date=|website=Singletrack|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> [[Glentrool]] is another 7 stanes site within Galloway Forest Park, an officially designated [[Dark Sky Park]] area.\n[[File:The Gem Stane at Kirroughtree - geograph.org.uk - 995803.jpg|thumb|The Gem Stane at Kirroughtree|alt=]]\nKnown as the 7stanes because each venue features a 'stane' ([[Scots language|Scots]] for stone), created by artist [[Gordon Young (artist)|Gordon Young]]. The 'Gem Stane' at Kirroughtree is a 1.75 ton stone sculpture made from Scottish pink quartz. Kirroughtree's trails are known as the 7stanes' hidden gem, and the forest is close to the [[Creetown]] Gem Rock Museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gordonyoung.net/scotland_7stanes.html|title=The 7stanes / Scotland, 2008|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Gordon Young|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006194912/http://gordonyoung.net/scotland_7stanes.html|archive-date=6 October 2014|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKirroughtree was winner of ''MBR Trail of the Year'' in 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.7stanes.com/kirroughtree-mbr-trail-of-the-year-i601975.html|title=Kirroughtree - MBR Trail of the Year.|website=7stanes.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101008195634/http://www.7stanes.com/kirroughtree-mbr-trail-of-the-year-i601975.html|archive-date=8 October 2010|access-date=8 November 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>. A new trail centre with restaurant and bike shop/hire was opened in 2014.\n\nKirroughtree has several cross-country XC trails (graded for varying levels of experience) and a skills area for practising mountain biking techniques:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/images/pdf/rec_pdfs/7stanes_Kirroughtree_trail_map__info.pdf|title=7stanes Kirroughtree Trail Map Info|last=|first=|date=|website=Forest and Land Scotland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* '''Bargary Wood''': green (easy), 3.8 miles (6.0 km), 10% singletrack\n* '''Larg Hill''': blue (moderate), 6.3 miles (10.0 km), 50% singletrack, with '''Doon Hill''' extension: 2.5 miles (4.0 km), 10% singletrack\n* '''The Twister''': red (difficult), 10.6 miles (17.0 km), 85% singletrack\n* '''Black Craigs''' (an extension to The Twister loop): black (severe/expert), 8.7 miles (14.0 km), 75% singletrack. The highlight is the unique 'McMoab' granite outcrop, with its huge slabs and ridges linked by boulder causeways. McMoab is named after the world famous mountain biking area at [[Moab, Utah|Moab]], Utah in USA. The gruelling climb of 'Heartbreak Hill' leads on to several downhill sections including the challenging 'Hissing Sid'.\n\n[[File:McMoab at Kirroughtree MTB Trail June 2007.jpg|thumb|270x270px|McMoab at Kirroughtree MTB Trail]]\n\n=== Long distance cycle route ===\n[[National Cycle Route 7]] (running 200 miles from Glasgow to Carlisle via Dumfries and Glen Trool) winds through the Forest Park.\n\n=== Fishing ===\nThere\u2019s are several locations for fishing in the Forest Park (mostly for [[brown trout]] and [[Northern pike|pike]]), at Loch Braden, Loch Dee, Black Loch, Spectacle Loch and Garwachie.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://forestryandland.gov.scot/visit/activities/mountain-biking/7stanes 7Stanes]\n\n[[Category:Forests and woodlands of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Mountain biking venues in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Dumfries and Galloway]]\n[[Category:Cycleways in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mountain biking routes in Galloway, Scotland}}\n{{Infobox forest|map=Scotland|map_caption=|relief=yes|county=Dumfries and Galloway|country=Scotland|coordinates={{Coord|54|57|14|N|4|25|18|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}|photo=Cycle Trail in Kirroughtree Forest - geograph.org.uk - 431790.jpg|photo_caption=Cycle Trail in Kirroughtree Forest}}{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n \n'''Kirroughtree Forest''' is located near [[Newton Stewart]] in [[Dumfries and Galloway]], southwest [[Scotland]] and overlooks the [[Irish Sea]]. It is managed by [[Forestry and Land Scotland]] and is part of the [[Galloway Forest Park]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/visit/forest-parks/galloway-forest-park|title=Galloway Forest Park|website=Forestry and Land Scotland|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> It has been developed as a centre for [[mountain biking]] trails. \n\nPalnure Burn is a small river which runs through the forest and on into the [[River Cree]]. The forest is home to red squirrels, red deer and ospreys.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/visit/forest-parks/galloway-forest-park/kirroughtree-visitor-centre|title=Kirroughtree Visitor Centre - Forestry and Land Scotland|last=|first=|date=|website=forestryandland.gov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Tourism ==\nKirroughtree atrracts about 78,000 visitors a year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/blog/investing-and-growing-the-visitor-footfall-and-the-profile-of-the-national-forest-estate|title=Investing and growing the visitor footfall and the profile of the National Forest Estate|last=|first=|date=|website=Forestry and Land Scotland|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Mountain biking ===\nKirroughtree is a [[mountain biking]] centre, which is one of 7 venues of the [[7Stanes]] project throughout the [[Scottish Borders]] and Dumfries and Galloway.<ref name=\":0\" /> 7stanes was started by the [[Forestry Commission]] in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://headwaterseconomics.org/wp-content/uploads/Trail_Study_81-7stanes-economic-impact.pdf|title=7 Stanes Phase 2 Evaluation|last=|first=|date=October 2007|website=Headwater Economics|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Chris Ross of the Forestry Commision led the design and construction of the Kirroughtree trails.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://singletrackworld.com/forum/topic/who-designed-and-constructed-the-7-stanes/|title=Who designed and constructed the 7 stanes?|last=|first=|date=|website=Singletrack|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> [[Glentrool]] is another 7 stanes site within Galloway Forest Park, an officially designated [[Dark Sky Park]] area. .\n[[File:The Gem Stane at Kirroughtree - geograph.org.uk - 995803.jpg|thumb|The Gem Stane at Kirroughtree|alt=]]\nKnown as the 7stanes because each venue features a 'stane' ([[Scots language|Scots]] for stone), created by artist [[Gordon Young (artist)|Gordon Young]]. The 'Gem Stane' at Kirroughtree is a 1.75 ton stone sculpture made from Scottish pink quartz. Kirroughtree's trails are known as the 7stanes' hidden gem, and the forest is close to the [[Creetown]] Gem Rock Museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gordonyoung.net/scotland_7stanes.html|title=The 7stanes / Scotland, 2008|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Gordon Young|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006194912/http://gordonyoung.net/scotland_7stanes.html|archive-date=6 October 2014|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKirroughtree was winner of ''MBR Trail of the Year'' in 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.7stanes.com/kirroughtree-mbr-trail-of-the-year-i601975.html|title=Kirroughtree - MBR Trail of the Year.|website=7stanes.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101008195634/http://www.7stanes.com/kirroughtree-mbr-trail-of-the-year-i601975.html|archive-date=8 October 2010|access-date=8 November 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>. A new trail centre with restaurant and bike shop/hire was opened in 2014.\n\nKirroughtree has several cross-country XC trails (graded for varying levels of experience) and a skills area for practising mountain biking techniques:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/images/pdf/rec_pdfs/7stanes_Kirroughtree_trail_map__info.pdf|title=7stanes Kirroughtree Trail Map Info|last=|first=|date=|website=Forest and Land Scotland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* '''Bargary Wood''': green (easy), 3.8 miles (6.0 km), 10% singletrack\n* '''Larg Hill''': blue (moderate), 6.3 miles (10.0 km), 50% singletrack, with '''Doon Hill''' extension: 2.5 miles (4.0 km), 10% singletrack\n* '''The Twister''': red (difficult), 10.6 miles (17.0 km), 85% singletrack\n* '''Black Craigs''' (an extension to The Twister loop): black (severe/expert), 8.7 miles (14.0 km), 75% singletrack. The highlight is the unique 'McMoab' granite outcrop, with its huge slabs and ridges linked by boulder causeways. McMoab is named after the world famous mountain biking area at [[Moab, Utah|Moab]], Utah in USA. The gruelling climb of 'Heartbreak Hill' leads on to several downhill sections including the challenging 'Hissing Sid'.\n\n[[File:McMoab at Kirroughtree MTB Trail June 2007.jpg|thumb|270x270px|McMoab at Kirroughtree MTB Trail]]\n\n=== Long distance cycle route ===\n[[National Cycle Route 7]] (running 200 miles from Glasgow to Carlisle via Dumfries and Glen Trool) winds through the Forest Park.\n\n=== Fishing ===\nThere\u2019s are several locations for fishing in the Forest Park (mostly for [[brown trout]] and [[Northern pike|pike]]), at Loch Braden, Loch Dee, Black Loch, Spectacle Loch and Garwachie.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://forestryandland.gov.scot/visit/activities/mountain-biking/7stanes 7Stanes]\n\n[[Category:Forests and woodlands of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Mountain biking venues in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Dumfries and Galloway]]\n[[Category:Cycleways in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Nick Number", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp commissionWP:TYPO", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kirroughtree"}
{"title_page": "Aframax", "text_new": "An '''Aframax''' ship is an [[Petroleum tanker|oil tanker]] with a deadweight between 80,000 and 120,000 metric tonnes. The term is based on the '''Average Freight Rate Association''' ('''AFRA'''), a [[Tanker (ship)|tanker]] rate system created in 1954 by [[Shell Oil]] to standardize shipping contract terms.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shipping Terms - Aframax|url=http://maritime-connector.com/wiki/aframax/|publisher=Maritime Connector|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nDue to their favorable size, Aframax tankers can serve most ports in the world. These vessels serve regions that do not have very large ports or offshore oil terminals to accommodate very large crude carriers and ultra-large crude carriers. Aframax tankers are optimal for short- to medium-haul crude oil transportation. Aframax class tankers are largely used in the basins of the [[Black Sea]], the [[North Sea]], the [[Caribbean Sea]], the [[South China Sea|South]] and [[East China Sea]]s, and the [[Mediterranean]]. Non\u2013[[OPEC]] exporting countries may require the use of this type of vessel because the harbors and canals through which these countries export their oil are too small to accommodate the larger [[Suezmax]] or the larger still [[Oil tanker#Size categories|very large crude carriers and ultra-large crude carriers]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Panamax ports]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://maritime-connector.com/wiki/ship-sizes/ Ship sizes]\n\n{{Ship measurements}}\n\n[[Category:Ship types]]\n[[Category:Oil tankers|+]]\n[[Category:Ship measurements]]\n\n\n{{Ship-type-stub}}\n", "text_old": "An '''Aframax''' ship is an [[Petroleum tanker|oil tanker]] smaller than 120,000 metric tonnes. The term is based on the '''Average Freight Rate Assessment''' ('''AFRA'''), a [[Tanker (ship)|tanker]] rate system created in 1954 by [[Shell Oil]] to standardise shipping contract terms.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shipping Terms - Aframax|url=http://maritime-connector.com/wiki/aframax/|publisher=Maritime Connector|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nDue to their favorable size, Aframax tankers can serve most ports in the world. These vessels serve regions that do not have very large ports or offshore oil terminals to accommodate very large crude carriers and ultra-large crude carriers. Aframax tankers are optimal for short- to medium-haul crude oil transportation. Aframax class tankers are largely used in the basins of the [[Black Sea]], the [[North Sea]], the [[Caribbean Sea]], the [[South China Sea|South]] and [[East China Sea]]s, and the [[Mediterranean]]. Non\u2013[[OPEC]] exporting countries may require the use of this type of vessel because the harbors and canals through which these countries export their oil are too small to accommodate the larger [[Suezmax]] or the larger still [[Oil tanker#Size categories|very large crude carriers and ultra-large crude carriers]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Panamax ports]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://maritime-connector.com/wiki/ship-sizes/ Ship sizes]\n\n{{Ship measurements}}\n\n[[Category:Ship types]]\n[[Category:Oil tankers|+]]\n[[Category:Ship measurements]]\n\n\n{{Ship-type-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SpaceNavy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added lower end of Aframax weight (80,000), changed Assessment to Association for the acronym description of AFRA, corrected misspelled word\" standarise\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aframax"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in London", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in London, England}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in London\n| width           =\n| image           =\n| image_size      =\n| image_upright   =\n| alt             =\n| caption         =\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak London per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per 10,000 residents by borough\n| map2            =\n| legend2         =\n| map3            =\n| legend3         =\n| map4            =\n| legend4         =\n| map5            =\n| legend5         =\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[London]], [[England]]\n| first_case      = 12 February 2020\n| arrival_date    =\n| date            =\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| confirmed_cases = 17,479<ref name=\"PHEupdate\"/> (as of 11 April)\n| suspected_cases =\n| severe_cases    =\n| recovery_cases  =\n| deaths          = 2,707<ref name=\"LondonGov\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus numbers in London |url=https://www.london.gov.uk/coronavirus/coronavirus-numbers-london |website=London.Gov.UK |publisher=Mayor of London |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> (as of 11 April)\n| territories     =\n| total_ili       =\n| website         = {{URL|https://www.london.gov.uk/coronavirus}}\n}}\nThe first [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] case in [[London]], England, was confirmed on 12 February 2020 in a woman who had recently arrived from China, where the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] began. \n\nAs of 11 April 2020, London is one of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in England|worst affected regions of England]], with 17,479 cases,<ref name=\"PHEupdate\">{{cite web |title=Total UK COVID-19 Cases Update |url=https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/f94c3c90da5b4e9f9a0b19484dd4bb14 |website=Public Health England |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> and 2,707 deaths.<ref name=\"LondonGov\"/>\n\n== History ==\nThe first confirmed case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in London was detected on 12 February 2020, in a woman who had arrived from China with the virus a few days earlier. She was the ninth case in the UK.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Ninth case found in UK |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51481469 |newspaper=BBC News |date=12 February 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 17 March, there had been almost 500 confirmed cases in London and 23 deaths, and [[Mayor of London]] [[Sadiq Khan]] announced the [[London Underground]] would begin running a reduced service due to the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-51929558|title=Coronavirus: Pictures show London's empty streets|date=17 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=18 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref> A day earlier [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|UK Prime Minister]] [[Boris Johnson]] had stated that London's outbreak was a few weeks ahead of the rest of the UK.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-51910748|title=Coronavirus 'spreading more rapidly' in London|date=16 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=18 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref> The city had seen the most cases of any UK region, with numbers rising much faster than elsewhere in the UK.<ref>{{Cite news|last=O'Carroll|first=Lisa |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/coronavirus-spreading-in-london-fastest-in-uk|title=Coronavirus spreading fastest in UK in London|date=16 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark]] and [[City of Westminster|Westminster]] were the worst affected boroughs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cityam.com/coronavirus-worst-affected-london-boroughs/|title=London coronavirus cases: Number of Covid-19 infections in your borough|date=18 March 2020|website=CityAM|language=en-GB|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> By 10 April, the five worst affected boroughs were [[London Borough of Brent|Brent]] (912 cases), [[London Borough of Croydon|Croydon]] (853), [[London Borough of Barnet|Barnet]] (837), Southwark (826) and [[London Borough of Lambeth|Lambeth]] (794).<ref name=\"PHEupdate\"/>\n\n==Response by sector==\n=== NHS ===\n[[File:NHS Nightingale Hospital London main entrance (2) (cropped).jpg|thumb|NHS Nightingale Hospital London]]\nWith a high number of cases, older populations and lower number of pre-Covid-19 critical care beds, [[district general hospital]]s, located around the centre of London were found in an analysis by Edge Health, to have experienced significant demand.<ref name=Batchelor9Apr2020>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/quality-and-performance/revealed-the-hospitals-facing-most-pressure-to-meet-coronavirus-demand/7027354.article|title=Revealed: The hospitals facing most pressure to meet coronavirus demand|last=Batchelor|first=George|date=9 April 2020|website=[[Health Service Journal]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On the evening of 19 March, [[Northwick Park Hospital]] in [[Harrow, London|Harrow]] said it had no critical care capacity left and was contacting neighbouring hospitals about transferring patients who need critical care to other sites.<ref name=Dunhill20March2020>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/news/hospitals-critical-care-unit-overwhelmed-by-coronavirus-patients/7027189.article|title=Hospital's critical care unit overwhelmed by coronavirus patients|last=Dunhill|first=Lawrence|date=20 March 2020|website=Health Service Journal|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On 4 April, [[Watford General Hospital]] also declared a 'critical incident'.<ref name=\"Skoulding-04Apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Skoulding |first1=Lucy |title=London coronavirus: People asked not to attend Watford General Hospital A&E 'even in an emergency' |url=https://www.mylondon.news/news/west-london-news/london-coronavirus-people-asked-not-18044018 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=MyLondon |date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, on 24 March, health secretary Matt Hancock said that a temporary new hospital, the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital]], was to be opened in the [[ExCeL London|ExCeL Centre]] in east London the following week. This [[NHS COVID-19 critical care hospitals|critical care hospital]] would provide up to 4,000 extra critical care beds for London.<ref name=Sengupta>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-military-london-excel-centre-nightingale-hospital-nhs-a9422026.html |title=Coronavirus: Emergency hospital to be set up in London's ExCel centre |last=Sengupta |first=Kim |date=24 March 2020 |work=Independent}}</ref>  The London hospital opened on 3 April,<ref>{{cite news |title=First coronavirus field hospital opens in London |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52150598 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> and received its first patients on 7 April.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52208156 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson spends second night in intensive care |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Public transport ===\n[[File:Stay at home and social distancing notices London Underground 27 March 2020.jpg|thumb|Stay at home and social distancing notices London Underground March 2020]]\nThe [[Waterloo & City line]], several tube stations and the [[Night Tube]] were suspended on 19 March,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-london-shops-could-close-and-transport-restricted-by-weekend-whitehall-sources-11959814|title=Coronavirus: London cuts Tube trains and warns 'don't travel unless you really have to'|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> with the [[Mayor of London]] and [[Transport for London]] (TfL) urging people to only use public transport if absolutely essential so that it can be used by critical workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tfl.gov.uk/info-for/media/press-releases/2020/march/planned-services-to-support-london-s-critical-workers|title=Planned services to support London's critical workers|website=Transport for London|language=en|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> From 20 March, 40 tube stations were closed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-london-shops-could-close-and-transport-restricted-by-weekend-whitehall-sources-11959814 |title=Coronavirus: London cuts Tube trains and warns 'don't travel unless you really have to' |website=Sky News |language=en|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321052444/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-london-shops-could-close-and-transport-restricted-by-weekend-whitehall-sources-11959814|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]] became the first [[train operating company]] to announce a reduced timetable, which would come into use from 23 March.<ref>[https://www.kentlive.news/news/kent-news/kent-coronavirus-southeastern-makes-major-3966534 Kent Coronavirus southeastern makes major] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320201805/https://www.kentlive.news/news/kent-news/kent-coronavirus-southeastern-makes-major-3966534 |date=20 March 2020 }} ''www.kentlive.news''</ref> From 30 March, the [[Gatwick Express]] service was suspended.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hastingsobserver.co.uk/news/politics/coronavirus-gatwick-express-trains-suspended-further-reductions-southern-and-thameslink-services-2518652|title=Coronavirus: Gatwick Express trains suspended with further reductions to Southern and Thameslink services|last=Powling|first=Joshua|date=2020-03-26|website=Hastings & St Leonards Observer|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nThe London Underground brought in new measures on 25 March to combat the spread of the virus, by slowing the flow of passengers onto platforms. Measures included the imposition of queuing at ticket gates and turning off some escalators.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-52023580 |title=New Tube restrictions to stop non-essential trips |date=25 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, [[London City Airport]] announced it would temporarily close due to the coronavirus outbreak.<ref name=\"BBC-25Mar2020\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: London City Airport to shut due to outbreak |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52038293 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Heathrow Airport closed one runway from 6 April, while [[Gatwick Airport]] closed one of its two terminals, and said its runway would open for scheduled flights only between 2pm and 10pm.<ref name=\"Morrison-03Apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Morrison |first1=Sean |title=London Heathrow to close runway as it scales back operations due to coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/london-heathrow-to-close-runway-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic-a4405711.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nBy 17 March most universities in London had suspended face-to-face learning or were planning to do so by 23 March, many moving classes online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mylondon.news/news/zone-1-news/london-coronavirus-london-universities-closing-17938646|title=All the latest London universities closing because of coronavirus|last=Lawrence-Jones|first=Charlie|date=17 March 2020|website=getwestlondon|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> It was announced on 18 March that schools in London would close by 20 March, as in the rest of the UK.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51952314|title=UK schools to close from Friday|date=18 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=19 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Data==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Confirmed cases !! New cases !! Total deaths !! New deaths\n|-\n| 03-11 ||  104  || 13 (+14%) || 7 || 4 (+133%)\n|-\n| 03-12 ||  136  || 32 (+31%) || 9 || 2 (+29%)\n|-\n| 03-13 ||  167  || 31 (+23%) || 15 || 6 (+67%)\n|-\n| 03-14 ||  313  || 146 (+87%) || 27 || 12 (+80%)\n|-\n| 03-15 ||  407  || 94 (+30%) || 36 || 9 (+33%)\n|-\n| 03-16 ||  480  || 73 (+18%) || 51 || 15 (+42%)\n|-\n| 03-17 ||  621  || 141 (+29%) || 70 || 19 (+37%)\n|-\n| 03-18 ||  953  || 332 (+53%) || 94 || 24 (+34%)\n|-\n| 03-19 || 1,221 || 268 (+28%) || 111 || 17 (+18%)\n|-\n| 03-20 || 1,588 || 367 (+30%) || 152 || 41 (+37%)\n|-\n| 03-21 || 1,965 || 377 (+24%) || 197 || 45 (+30%)\n|-\n| 03-22 || 2,189 || 224 (+11%) || 235 || 38 (+19%)\n|-\n| 03-23 || 2,433 || 244 (+11%) || 265 || 30 (+13%)\n|-\n| 03-24 || 2,872 || 439 (+18%) || 313 || 48 (+18%)\n|-\n| 03-25 || 3,247 || 375 (+13%) || 390 || 77 (+25%)\n|-\n| 03-26 || 3,919 || 672 (+21%) || 500 || 110 (+28%)\n|-\n| 03-27 || 4,637 || 718 (+18%) || 610 || 110 (+22%)\n|-\n| 03-28 || 5,299 || 662 (+14%) || 717 || 107 (+18%)\n|-\n| 03-29 || 5,957 || 658 (+12%) || 884 || 167 (+23%)\n|-\n| 03-30 || 6,521 || 564 (+9%) || 1038 || 154 (+17%)\n|-\n| 03-31 || 7,121 || 600 (+9%) || 1129 || 91 (+9%)\n|-\n| 04-01 || 8,341 || 1,220 (+17%) || 1291 || 162 (+14%)\n|-\n| 04-02 || 9,291 || 950 (+11%) || 1452 || 161 (+12%)\n|-\n| 04-03 || 10,247|| 956 (+10%) || 1579 || 127 (+9%)\n|-\n| 04-04 || 10,764|| 517 (+5%) || 1753 || 174 (+11%)\n|-\n| 04-05 || 11,978|| 1,214 (+11%) || 1882 || 129 (+7%)\n|-\n| 04-06 || 12,636|| 658 (+5%) || 2106 || 224 (+12%)\n|-\n| 04-07 || 13,378|| 742 (+6%) || 2307 || 201 (+10%)\n|-\n| 04-08 || 14,355|| 977 (+7%) || 2520 || 213 (+9%)\n|-\n| 04-09 || 15,271|| 916 (+6%) || 2769 || 249 (+10%)\n|-\n| 04-10 || 16,011|| 740 (+5%) || 2977 || 208 (+8%)\n|-\n| 04-11 || 16,721|| 710 (+4%) || 3107 || 130 (+